\newline 

\backslash 
end{keywords}
\end_inset 


\layout Section

Introduction 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Introduction}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars (TTS) are young (
\begin_inset Formula $<\sim3\times10^{6}\,\mathrm{yrs}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{appenzeller:1989}
\end_inset 

) low-mass stars, and known as progenitors of solar-type stars.
 Classical T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars (CTTS) exhibit strong H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission, and typically have spectral types of F--K.
 Some of the most active CTTS show emission in higher Balmer lines and metal
 lines (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
ion{Ca}{ii}
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
H and K).
 They also exhibit an excess amount of continuum flux in the ultraviolet
 (UV) and infrared (IR).
 Their spectral energy distribution and polarization data suggest the presence
 of a circumstellar disc, and it plays an important role in regulating dynamics
 of gas flows around CTTS.
\layout Standard

Many observational studies (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{herbig:1962}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{edwards:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kenyon:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

) of CTTS line profiles show evidences for both outward wind flows and inward
 accretion flows, as seen in the blue-shifted absorption features in H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles and the redshifted inverse P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni (IPC) profiles respectively.
 Typical mass-loss rates of CTTS are about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-9}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kuhi:1964}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{edwards:1987}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartigan:1995}
\end_inset 

), and the mass-accretion rates are also about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-9}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kenyon:1987}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{bertout:1988}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{gullbring:1998}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

Recent H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 spectro-astrometric observations by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{takami:2003}
\end_inset 

 show the direct evidence for the presence of bipolar and monopolar outflows
 down to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1\,\mathrm{AU}$
\end_inset 

 scale (e.g.
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
,
\end_inset 

CS\SpecialChar ~
Cha and RU\SpecialChar ~
Lup).
 Similarly, ESO VLT observation of high-resolution (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{R=50\,000}$
\end_inset 

) two-dimensional spectral of edge-on CTTS (HH30
\begin_inset Formula $^{*}$
\end_inset 

, HK\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
B, and HV\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
C) by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

 show the extended H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission in the direction perpendicular to the obscuring circumstellar
 disc, and in both above and below the disc --- suggesting the presence
 of the bipolar outflows.
 In slightly larger scale, 
\emph on 
HST 
\emph default 
observation of HH30 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{burrows:1996}
\end_inset 

 shows the jet traced to within 
\begin_inset Formula $\lesssim30$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU from the star.
 The jet has a cone shape with an opening angle of 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

 between 70 and 700 AU 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

 found about 80 per cent of their samples (30 CTTS) show blue-shifted absorption
 components in at least one of Balmer lines and Ca\SpecialChar ~
K (most commonly in H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

In a currently favoured model of accretion flows around CTTS, the accretion
 discs are disrupted by the magnetosphere of stars which channels the gas
 from the disc onto the surface of the stars (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{uchida:1985}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:1991}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{cameron:1993}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{shu:1994}
\end_inset 

).
 This picture of the accretion flows is supported by the evidences that
 CTTS have relatively strong (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{3}\mathrm{G}$
\end_inset 

) magnetic field (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{jonhs-krull:1999}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{guenther:1996}
\end_inset 

) and by the radiative transfer models which reproduce the observed profiles
 for some TTS (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

).
 The magnetospherical accretion model naturally explains the blue-ward asymmetri
c emission lines (seen in some of CTTS) caused by the partial occultation
 of the flow by the disc, and the redshifted absorption component at the
 typical free-fall velocities (a few hundred 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

) seen in some of CTTS.
 Despite the success of the magnetospherical accretion model in explaining
 the line profiles in some CTTS, the overwhelming observational evidences
 for the outflow (mentioned above) in the CTTS profiles suggests that this
 model is only a part of a whole picture.
 Clearly, the modification to include the out-flowing wind/jet flow is necessary
 if one requires to predict the mass-accretion rate and the mass-loss rate
 of CTTS by modelling their emission profiles (e.g.
 H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Priory to the magnetospherical models, many alternative models had been
 considered to explain the observed spectroscopic features mentioned earlier.
 For example, (1)\SpecialChar ~
the Alfv
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
'{e}
\end_inset 

n wave-driven wind model (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{decampli:1981}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartmann:1982}
\end_inset 

), (2)\SpecialChar ~
turbulent boundary layer (between the accretion disc and stellar surface)
 model (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{bertout:1988}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{basri:1989}
\end_inset 

), (3)\SpecialChar ~
chromospheric model (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{calvet:1984}
\end_inset 

), and (4)\SpecialChar ~
disc wind model (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{calvet:1992b}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kwan:1995}
\end_inset 

).
 Considering the success of the magnetospherical accretion flow model in
 some cases and the observational evidences for the outflows, it is likely
 that an improved spectroscopic model requires both inflow and outflow component
s.
 The combination of the magnetospheric accretion flow model with model 1
 or 4 would be a reasonable starting point.
 Although time consuming to explore a larger parameter space, more realistic
 density, velocity and temperature structure from magnetohydrodynamic wind+accre
tion models should be considered as inputs for an radiative transfer model
 in the future.
 
\layout Standard

Recent work by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2005}
\end_inset 

 showed the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

, H
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and Na\SpecialChar ~
D lines of RW Aur are better produced by the radiative transfer model
 which include the collimated disc-wind arising from near the inner edge
 of the accretion disc.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{malbet:2005}
\end_inset 

 considered the combination of a spherical wind and the accretion disc in
 their radiative transfer model to reproduce Br
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 from the early-type Herbig Be star MWC\SpecialChar ~
297.
 
\layout Standard

The magneto-centrifugal wind model, first proposed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{blandford:1982}
\end_inset 

, has been often used to reproduce the large-scale wind structure of T Tauri
 stars, or to model observed optical jets (e.g.\SpecialChar ~
HH\SpecialChar ~
30 jet by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{burrows:1996}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{ray:1996}
\end_inset 

).
 The launching of the wind from a Keplerian disc is typically done by treating
 the equatorial plane of the disc as a mass-injecting boundary condition
 (e.g., 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{shu:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{ustyugova:1995}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{ouyed:1997}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

).
 Depending on the location of the open magnetic fields anchored to the disc,
 two different types of winds are produced.
 If the field is constrained to be near the co-rotation radius of stellar
 magnetosphere, an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

X-wind
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{shu:1994}
\end_inset 

 is produces.
 If the open field lines are located in a wider area of the disc, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

disc-wind
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 similar to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

 is produced 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

.
 Recent reviews on the jet/wind-disc connection can be found in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{pudritz:2005}
\end_inset 

.
 Interestingly, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{matt:2005}
\end_inset 

 showed the possiblity that the stellar wind along the open magnetic field
 originating from the star can cause significant spin-down torque on the
 star, provided that mass-loss rate is high enough.
\layout Standard

The main aim of this paper is to find a simple kinematic model which can
 reproduce the wide variety of the observed profiles, and to perform the
 empirical studies of the line formation.
 More specifically, we present disc--wind--magnetosphere hybrid models for
 CTTS, and perform parametric studies of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 formation.
 This study should provide preliminary physical conditions which lead to
 the wide variety of emission line profiles seen in the observation, and
 would help to construct more comprehensive circumstellar models (e.g.
 via MHD simulations) of T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars.
 the Using the model results, we examine the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 spectroscopic classification used by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

, and compare models with observations.
 We will also discuss whether our model is consistent with some predictions
 made by the recent MHD studies i.e.\SpecialChar ~
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}/\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}\approx0.1$
\end_inset 

 (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

In section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:model-configuration}

\end_inset 

, the model assumptions, and the basic model configurations are presented.
 We discuss the radiative transfer model used to compute the profiles in
 section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:radiative-transfer-model}

\end_inset 

, and the results of model calculations are given in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Results}

\end_inset 

.
 The closer examination and discussion of the results are presented in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Discussion}

\end_inset 

.
 Finally, the summary of this work and the conclusion are in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Conclusions}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

Model configuration
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:model-configuration}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

To understand how the different part of the CTTS circumstellar environment
 contributes to the formation of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

, the model spaced is divided into four different regions: 1.\SpecialChar ~
Central continuum
 source, 2.\SpecialChar ~
magnetosphere accretion flow, 3.\SpecialChar ~
wind outflow, and 4.\SpecialChar ~
accretion disc.
 Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

 depicts the relative location in the model space.
 In all regions, the density is symmetric around the z-axis.
 The innermost radius of the magnetosphere at the equatorial plane coincides
 with the the inner radius of the accretion disc.
 From the inner most part of the accretion disc, the gas freely fall, moving
 along the magnetic filed onto the surface of the star.
 For the purpose of computational simplicity, the collimated bipolar wind
 are defined only in the outside of the largest radius of the magnetosphere
 (to avoid overlapping of the wind with the magnetosphere).
 In the following subsections, the details of model components will be described.
 In our models, two different types of the wind configurations are consisdered:
 (1)\SpecialChar ~
the bipolar wind resembling the density structure of the MHD simulation
 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in large scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 

, and (2) that in small scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Alternative-model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard


