\begin_inset Note
collapsed false

\layout Standard

Maybe you should plot 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}$
\end_inset 

here also!
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{The dependency of the wind velocity and density structures on the wind accerelation parameter $
\backslash 
beta$. The radial component of the wind/jet velocity (equation~
\backslash 
ref{eq:wind_velocity_radial_part}) in polar direction, $
\backslash 
theta = 0$ as a function of radius is shown on left. The wind density (equation~
\backslash 
ref{eq:wind_density_final} along polar direction as a function of radius is shown on right. For all $
\backslash 
beta$ values, the density is normalized to the desnity at the base of the wind in polar direction, i.e. $
\backslash 
rho_0 = 
\backslash 
rho
\backslash 
left(R_
\backslash 
mathrm{mo},0
\backslash 
right)$.  The smaller the value of $
\backslash 
beta$, the faster the accerelation of the wind. For the raidus ($r/R_{
\backslash 
mathrm{mo}} < 10$, both velocity and density are sensitive to the value of $
\backslash 
beta$. For all $
\backslash 
beta$ values, the radial velocity of the wind reaches the terminal velocity ($
\backslash 
sim 210
\backslash 
,
\backslash 
kmps$ by  $r/R_{
\backslash 
mathrm{mo}} 
\backslash 
sim 1000$. The initial velocity $V_{0}=10
\backslash 
,
\backslash 
kmps$, which approximately corresponds to the thermal velocity of a hydrogen atom at 7500~K,  is used for all $v_{r}$ plots. Beyound $r/R_{
\backslash 
mathrm{mo}}= 100$, little difference is seen in the polar density with diffrent $
\backslash 
beta$ values.}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{figure*}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
