\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Accretion disc
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Accretion-disc}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Region 4 in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 


\layout Subsubsection

Density and velocity
\layout Standard

Although it is possible, in our model, to compute the dust-sublimation radius
 and the vertical hydrostatic structure of the accretion disc self-consistently
 (assuming the radial dependency of the mid-plane density) by using the
 iterative Monte Carlo radiative transfer technique (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{walker:2004}
\end_inset 

), we find it to be too time consuming for the purpose of this paper --
 understanding the general characteristic of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profile shapes hence exploring a large parameter space.
 For this reason, we adopt a simple analytical disc model, the steady 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

-disc `standard model' (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{shakura:1973}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{frank:2002}
\end_inset 

) with the inner radius fixed at the inner radius of the magnetosphere (at
 equatorial plane).
 The disc density distribution is given by 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{d}}\left(w,z\right)=\Sigma\left(w\right)\,\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}h\left(w\right)}e^{-\left(\frac{z}{2h\left(w\right)}\right)^{2}}\label{eq:disc-density-function}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset 

 are the distance from the symmetry axis, the scale height, the distance
 from the disc plane, and the surface density at the mid-plane, respectively.
 The mid-plane surface density and the scale height are given as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Sigma\left(w\right)=\frac{5M_{\mathrm{d}}}{8\pi R_{\mathrm{do}}^{2}}\, w^{-3/4}\label{eq:density-midplane}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{do}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset 

 are the disc radius and the disc mass respectively.
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h\left(w\right)=0.05\, R_{\mathrm{do}}\, w^{9/8}\,.\label{eq:scale-height}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 With these parameters, the disc is slightly flared.
 The inner radius of the disc is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{di}}=R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 (the inner radius of the magnetosphere at the equatorial plane), which
 is approximately same as the co-rotating radius of the system with the
 parameters in Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

.
 The disc mass, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mathrm{d}}$
\end_inset 

, of an object is assumed to be 1/100 of the central mass (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{*}$
\end_inset 

), and the disc radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{di}}$
\end_inset 

) to be 100\SpecialChar ~
au.
 The velocity of the gas/dust in the disc is assumed to be Keplerian.
\layout Subsubsection

Dust model
\layout Standard

To calculate the dust scattering and absorption cross section as a function
 of wavelength, the optical constants of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{draine:1984}
\end_inset 

 for amorphous carbon grains and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hanner:1988}
\end_inset 

 for silicate grains are used.
 The model uses the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

large grain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 dust model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{wood:2002}
\end_inset 

 in which the dust grain size distribution is described by the following
 function:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n\left(a\right)da=\left(C_{\mathrm{C}}+C_{\mathrm{Si}}\right)\, a^{-p}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{a}{a_{c}}\right)^{q}\right]da\label{eq:grain-dist-function}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset 

 is the grain size restricted between 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{min}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{C}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Si}}$
\end_inset 

 are the terms set by requiring the grains to completely deplete a solar
 abundance carbon and silicon.
 The parameters adopted in our model are: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{C}}=1.32\times10^{-17}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Si}}=1.05\times10^{-17}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=3.0$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0.6$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{\mathrm{min}}}=0.1\,\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{\mu m}}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{\mathrm{max}}}=1000\,\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{\mu m}}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{c}=50\,\mathrm{\mathrm{\mathrm{\mu m}}}$
\end_inset 

.
 This corresponds to Model\SpecialChar ~
1 of the dust model used by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{wood:2002}
\end_inset 

.
 See also their Fig.\SpecialChar ~
3 The relative number of each grain is assumed to be
 that of solar abundance, C/H
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3.5\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{anders:1989}
\end_inset 

 and Si/H
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3.6\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{grevesse:1993}
\end_inset 

 which are similar to values found in the ISM model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{mathis:1977}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet*{kim:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 Similar abundances were used in the circumstellar disc models of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{cotera:2001}
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Subsection

Alternative model: disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Alternative-model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/discwind.eps
	scale 32
	keepAspectRatio

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{Basic Model Configuration. The system consist of four components: 1.~the continuum source located at the origin $
\backslash 
left( o 
\backslash 
right)$ of the cartisian coordinates $
\backslash 
left(x,y,z
\backslash 
right)$ -- the y-axis are into the paper, 2.~magnetospherical accretion flow, 3.~colliminated wind/jet outflow, and 4.~accretion disc. The density distribution is symmetric around the z-axis. The innermost raius of the magnetsphere (at the equotrial plane) coincides with the the inner radius of the accretion disc. From the inner most part of the accretion disc, the gas freely fall, moving along the magneic filed onto the surface of the star. For simplicit, the colliminated wind/jet exists outside of the largest radius of the magnesophere (dotted line). }
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig:config_discwind}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The wind model presented here is to simulate the collimated MHD disc-wind
 calculations of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in small scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 

 introduced the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

split-monopole
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 kinematic disc-wind model in their studies of the UV resonance lines formed
 in the winds of cataclysmic variable stars.
 In this model, the outflow arises from the surface of the rotating accretion
 disc, and has a biconical geometry.
 The specific angular momentum is assumed to be conserved along a stream
 line, and the poloidal velocity component is assumed to be simply a radial
 from vertically displaced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

sources
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 from the central star.
 We adopt their disc-wind model here, and consider the combined effect of
 the disc-wind and the magnetospherical accretion flow model described earlier.
 In the following, we briefly described their disc-wind model.
 For details of the models, readers are referred to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{long:2002}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Four basic parameters for the models are: 1.
 mass-loss rate, 2.\SpecialChar ~
the degree of the wind collimation, 3.\SpecialChar ~
velocity gradients,
 and 4.\SpecialChar ~
the wind temperature.
 The basic configuration of the disc-wind model is shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_discwind}

\end_inset 

.
 The disc wind originates from the disc surface, but the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 point (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset 

), from which the stream lines diverges, are placed at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

 above and below the centre of the star.
 By changing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, the degree of the wind collimation is controlled.
 The larger the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, the wind becomes more parallel to the rotation axis, i.e.
 the wind becomes more collimated.
 The mass-loss launching is restricted between 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wi}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wo}}$
\end_inset 

 where the former is set to be equal to the outer radius of the magnetosphere
 (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

) for simplicity and the latter is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU as in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The local mass-loss rate per unit area (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset 

) is assumed to be proportional to the mid-plane temperature of the disc,
 and is a function of the cylindrical radius 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset 

 , i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{m}\left(w\right)\propto T\left(w\right)^{\alpha}\,\,.\label{eq:discwind-massloss-temp}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Further, the mid-plane temperature of the disc is assumed to be expressed
 as a power-law in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

; thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $T\propto w^{q}$
\end_inset 

.
 Using this in the relation above, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{m}\left(w\right)\propto w^{p}\label{eq:discwind-massloss-w}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\alpha\times q$
\end_inset 

.
 The index of the mid-plane temperature power law is adopted from the dust
 radiative transfer model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{whitney:2003a}
\end_inset 

 who found the inner most part of the accretion disc has 
\begin_inset Formula $q=-1.15$
\end_inset 

.
 To be consistent with the collimated disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 who used 
\begin_inset Formula $p=-3/2$
\end_inset 

, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is set to 1.3.
 The constant of proportionality in equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:discwind-massloss-w}

\end_inset 

 is found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset 

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wi}}$
\end_inset 

to 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wo}}$
\end_inset 

, and the normalising the total mass-loss rate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

.
 (CHECK THE VALUE OF ALPHA AGAIN!)
\layout Standard

The azimuthal/rotational component of the wind velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}\left(w,z\right)$
\end_inset 

 is computed from the Keplerian rotational velocity at the emerging point
 of the stream line i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}\left(w_{i},0\right)=\left(GM_{*}/w_{i}\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset 

 is the distance from the rotational axis (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

) to the emerging point on the disc, and by assuming the conservation of
 the specific angular momentum along a stream line: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{\phi}\left(w,z\right)\,=v_{\phi}\left(w_{i},0\right)\,\left(\frac{w_{i}}{w}\right)\label{eq:discwind-toroidal-velocity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

.
 Based on the classic 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 velocity law of hot stellar winds (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{castor:1975}
\end_inset 

), the poloidal component of the wind velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{p}$
\end_inset 

) parameterised as: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{p}\left(w_{i},l\right)=c_{\mathrm{s}}\left(w_{i}\right)+\left[f\, v_{\mathrm{esc}}-c_{\mathrm{s}}\left(w_{i}\right)\right]\left(1-\frac{R_{s}}{l+R_{s}}\right)^{\beta}\label{eq:discwind-poloidal-velocity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\mathrm{s}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 are the sound speed at the wind launching point on the disc, the constant
 scale factor of the asymptotic terminal velocity to the local escape velocity
 (from the wind emerging point on the disc), and the distance from the disc
 surface along stream lines respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{s}$
\end_inset 

 is the wind scale length, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{s}=10\, R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 is adopted as similarly done by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{long:2002}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Assuming the mass-flux conservation and using the velocity field defined
 above, the disc wind density as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 can be written as
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(w_{i},l\right)=\frac{\dot{m}\left(w_{i}\right)}{v_{p}\left(w_{i},l\right)\,\left|\cos\delta\right|}\,\left\{ \frac{d}{Q\left(w_{i},l\right)\,\cos\delta}\right\} ^{2}\label{eq:discwind-density}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 are the distance from the source point (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset 

) to a point along the stream line and the angle between the stream line
 and the disc normal respectively.
\layout Standard

Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:discwind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

 shows the density and the velocity components along the mid stream line
 (passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\left(R_{\mathrm{wi}}+R_{\mathrm{wo}}\right)/2$
\end_inset 

 on the disc plane (
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset 

) for different values of the wind acceleration parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure*}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


