\end_inset 


\layout Section

Radiative transfer model
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:radiative-transfer-model}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We have extended the TORUS radiative transfer code (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{harries:2000}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kurosawa:2004a}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

) to compute the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles from pre-main-sequence stars which are surrounded by one or more
 of the followings: the magnetospherical accretion flow, the out-flowing
 collimated wind, and the accretion disc.
 Previously in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

, the model used in the three-dimensional (3-D) adaptive mesh refinement
 (AMR) to investigate the line variability mainly associated with rotational
 motion of complex geometrical configurations of magnetospherical flow (see
 also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{kurosawa:2005a}
\end_inset 

).
 We modified the code to handle the two-dimensional (2-D) density distribution,
 and restricted our models to be axi-symmetric.
 It was done so in order to enable us to explore rather large number of
 parameter spaces (c.f.\SpecialChar ~
section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:model-configuration}

\end_inset 

).
 Note that the velocity field is still in 3-D -- the third component can
 be calculated by using the symmetry for a given value of azimuthal angle.
 The examples of how the AMR grid for the purpose of the radiative transfer
 is constructed are presented in e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{wolf:1999}
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{kurosawa:2001a}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{steinacker:2003} 
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The computation of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is divided in two parts: 1.\SpecialChar ~
the source function calculation (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) and 2.\SpecialChar ~
the observed flux/profile calculation.
 In the first process, we have utilised the method by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 (see also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{rybicki:1978}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

) in which the Sobolev approximation method is applied.
 The population of the bound states of hydrogen are assumed to be in statistical
 equilibrium, and the gas to be in radiative equilibrium.
 Our hydrogen atom model consist of 14 bound state and continuum.
 Readers are refer to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 for details.
 (AND MORE..)
\layout Standard

To compute the observed line profile, the Monte Carlo radiative transfer
 method (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hillier:1991}
\end_inset 

) using the Sobolev escape-probability can be used when I.\SpecialChar ~
a large velocity
 gradient is present in the gas flow, and II.\SpecialChar ~
the intrinsic line width is
 negligible compared to the Doppler broadening of the line.
 In our earlier models (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{harries:2000}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

), this method was used to compute the line profiles since the condition
 I and II are reasonably satisfied.
 However, as noted and demonstrated by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

, even with a moderate amount of mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $~10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

), Stark broadening becomes important in the optically thick H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 line.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 (MORE REF HERE) also pointed out that the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

profiles from CTTS typically have the wings extending to 
\begin_inset Formula $500\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

(e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
cite{edwards:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

) which cannot be explained by the infall velocity of the gas along the
 magnetosphere.
 
\layout Standard

To implement the broadening mechanism, two modifications to our previous
 model (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

) are necessary.
 First, the emission and absorption profiles must be replaced by a Voigt
 profile which is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H\left(a,y\right)\equiv\frac{a}{\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-y'^{2}}}{\left(y-y'\right)^{2}+a^{2}}\, dy'\label{eq:voigt_profile_def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\Gamma/4\pi\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\left(\nu-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y'=\left(\nu'-\nu_{0}\right)/\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

 (c.f.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{mihalas:1978}
\end_inset 

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the line centre frequency, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}$
\end_inset 

 is the Doppler line width of hydrogen atom (due to its thermal motion)
 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu_{\mathrm{D}}=\left(2kT/m_{\mathrm{H}}\right)^{1/2}\times\left(\nu_{0}/c\right)$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 is the mass of a hydrogen atom.
 The damping constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset 

, which depends on the physical condition of the gas, is parameterised by
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet*{vernazza:1973}
\end_inset 

 as follows:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\Gamma & = & C_{\mathrm{rad}}+C_{\mathrm{vdW}}\left(\frac{n_{\mathrm{HI}}}{10^{16}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)\left(\frac{T}{5000\,\mathrm{K}}\right)^{0.3}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\, C_{\mathrm{Stark}}\left(\frac{n_{e}}{10^{12}\,\mathrm{cm^{-3}}}\right)^{2/3}\label{eq:dampimg_constant_def}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{H\, I}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{e}$
\end_inset 

 are the number density of neutral hydrogens and that of free electrons.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{rad}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{vdW}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Stark}}$
\end_inset 

 are natural broadening, van der Waals broadening, and linear Stark broadening
 constants respectively.
 We simply adopt this parameterisation along with the values of broadening
 constants for H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{luttermoser:1992}
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{rad}}=6.5\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{vdW}}=4.4\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\mathrm{Stark}}=1.17\times10^{-3}$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

.
 In terms of level populations and the Voigt profile, the line opacity for
 the transition 
\begin_inset Formula $i\rightarrow j$
\end_inset 

 can be written as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi_{l}=\frac{\pi^{1/2}e^{2}}{m_{e}c}f_{ij}n_{j}\left(1-\frac{g_{j}n_{i}}{g_{i}n_{j}}\right)H\left(a,y\right)\label{eq:line_opacity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}$
\end_inset 

 are the oscillator strength, the population of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

-th level, the population of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

-th level, the degeneracy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

-th level, and the degeneracy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

-th level respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{e}$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset 

 are the electron mass and charge (c.f.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{mihalas:1978}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

The second modification in our model is the replacement of the method of
 solving the formal solution from the Monte Carlo radiative transfer method
 with Sobolev approximation to the direct integration method.
 Similarly to the notation used by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

, we specify the cylindrical coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p,\, q,\, t\right)$
\end_inset 

 which is the original stellar coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\rho,\,\phi,\, z\right)$
\end_inset 

 rotated (around 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 axis) by the inclination of the line of sight, i.e.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

-axis coincides with the line of sight.
 The observed flux (
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{\nu}=\frac{1}{4\pi d^{2}}\int_{0}^{p_{\mathrm{max}}}\int_{0}^{2\pi}p\,\sin q\, I_{\nu}\mathrm{\, d}q\,\mathrm{d}p\label{eq:flux_integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are the distance to an observer, the maximum extent to the model space
 in the projected (rotated) plane, and the specific intensity (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) in the direction on observer at the outer boundary.
 For a given ray along 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

, the specific intensity is given by:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I_{\nu}=I_{0}e^{-\tau_{\infty}}+\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{\infty}}S_{\nu}\left(t\right)\, e^{-\tau}\mathrm{d}\tau\label{eq:formal_sol_integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are the intensity at the boundary on the opposite to the observer and the
 source function (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\nu}/\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) of the stellar atmosphere/wind at a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset 

.
 For a ray which intersects with the stellar core, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is computed from the stellar atmosphere mode of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{kurucz:1979}
\end_inset 

 as described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Continuum-Source}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}=0$
\end_inset 

 otherwise.
 The initial position of each ray is assigned to be at the centre of the
 surface element (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}A=p\,\sin q\,\mathrm{d}q\,\mathrm{dp}$
\end_inset 

).
 The code execution time is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}\, n_{q}\, n_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}$
\end_inset 

 are the number of cylindrical radial and angular points for the flux integratio
n, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

is the number of frequency points.
 In the models presented in the next (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Results}

\end_inset 

), 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=180$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{q}=100$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\nu}=101$
\end_inset 

 are used unless specified otherwise.
 The linearly spaced radial grid is used for the area where the ray intersects
 with magnetosphere, and the logarithmically spaced grid is used for the
 wind and the accretion disc regions.
\layout Standard

The optical depth 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:formal_sol_integral}

\end_inset 

 is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau\left(t\right)\equiv\int_{t}^{\infty}\chi_{\nu}\left(t'\right)\,\mathrm{d}t'\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 is the opacity of media the ray passes through.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 is the total optical depth measured from the initial ray point to the observer
 (or to the outer boundary closer to the observer).
 Initially, the optical depth segments 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d\tau}$
\end_inset 

 are computed at the intersections of a ray with the original AMR grid in
 which the opacity and emissivity information are stored.
 For high optical depth models, additional points are inserted between the
 original points along the ray, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

 values are interpolated to those points to ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}\tau<0.05$
\end_inset 

 for the all ray segments.
\layout Standard

For a point in the magnetosphere and the wind flows, the emissivity and
 the opacity of the media are given as:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}
\eta_{\nu} & = & \eta_{\mathrm{c}}^{\mathrm{H}}+\eta_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}\\
\chi_{\nu} & = & \chi_{c}^{\mathrm{H}}+\chi_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}+\sigma_{\mathrm{es}}\end{array}\right.\label{eq:emiss_opa_gas}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mathrm{c}}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

 are the continuum and line emissivity of hydrogen.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{c}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{l}^{\mathrm{H}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{es}}$
\end_inset 

 are the continuum, line opacity (equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:line_opacity}

\end_inset 

) of hydrogen, and the electron scattering opacity.
 Similarly, for a point in the accretion disc,
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}
\eta_{\nu} & = & 0\\
\chi_{\nu} & = & \kappa_{\mathrm{abs}}^{\mathrm{dust}}+\kappa_{\mathrm{sca}}^{\mathrm{dust}}\end{array}\right.\label{eq:emiss_opa_dust}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\mathrm{abs}}^{\mathrm{dust}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{\mathrm{sca}}^{\mathrm{dust}}$
\end_inset 

 are the dust absorption, and scattering opacity which are calculated using
 the dust property described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:grain-dist-function}

\end_inset 

.
 For computational simplicity, we assumed that the dust emissivity is zero.
 Since the disc mass of CTTS are rather small (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.1\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}}$
\end_inset 

) and low temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $<\sim1600\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

), the continuum flux contribution at H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 wavelength is expected to be negligible (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{chiang:1997}
\end_inset 

).
 The scattering flux by the accretion may become important for H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 for the edge-on (
\begin_inset Formula $i\sim90^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

) cases in which the disc obscures the stellar surface -- the main source
 of continuum flux.
 We examine this effect later in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-acc-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

Results
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Results}

\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Magnetosphere
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:model-acc}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Using the standard parameters (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

) for the central star and the magnetosphere, we examine the dependency
 of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 on the temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

) of accretion flow and the mass accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

), as similarly done by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 for H
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

.
 The hot ring temperature is computed from the available kinetic energy
 of the free-falling gas as describe by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 while 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 used the constant hot ring temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $8000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

) for most of their models.
 The accretion luminosity (
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

) of models with 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 is about a half of the total luminosity (without the hot ring) of the star,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

.
 The results are placed in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_acc_models}

\end_inset 

.
 Overall dependency on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

 are similar to that of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

.
 In general, the line strength becomes weaker as the accretion rate and
 the temperature become smaller.
 The red-shifted absorption becomes less visible for higher accretion rate
 and temperature models in which the flux in the damping wings become important.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:broadening}

\end_inset 

 shows an example of the effect of the broadening of H alpha (with 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

) due to the damping constants as described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:radiative-transfer-model}

\end_inset 

.
 Although the maximum flux of the model with the broadening is almost identical
 to that of the model with no damping constant (
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=0$
\end_inset 

), a significant increase of the line flux in both red and blue wings of
 seen in the model with broadening.
 A weak red-shifted absorption component (which is a signature of the magnetosph
erical accretion) is weakened or eliminated by the flux in broadened wing.
 
\layout Standard

Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:ha_ew_acc_models}

\end_inset 

 shows the EW for the models shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_acc_models}

\end_inset 

.
 About a half of the models shown the figure agree with the observed EW
 values of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from 30 TTS presented by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

 who found the EW of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 ranges from 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
,
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim160$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

, and the mean to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim55$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

.
 For the lowest 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

 models, the EW values are smaller than the minimum EW observed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

, and for some models the EWs are negative.
 Since the target selection criteria of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

 is not stated in their paper, we can not conclude that these low 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

models disagree with the observation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

, who measured the EW of 43 TTS and found similar distribution of EW values,
 mentioned that their EW measurements are under-representing real samples
 since the selection of the targets are based on the strong H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission in H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 surveys.
\layout Standard

The dependency of the profile on the inclination angle (
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

) is demonstrated in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:acc_inclination_effect}

\end_inset 

.
 The model uses the same parameters as in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:broadening}

\end_inset 

 (with broadening, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

).
 The figure show that the peak (normalised) flux decrease as the inclination
 angle increases.
 Similarly, the equivalent width also decreases as the inclination increases.
 Because of the geometry of the magnetospherical accretion (c.f.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

) and of the presence of the gas with the highest velocity close to the
 stellar surface, the highest red-shifted line-of-sight velocity is visible
 only at the high inclination angles.
 This explains the wider appearance of the profile with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=80^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

compared to the relatively narrow line appearance of the profile with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=10^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 Although not show here, a similar dependency on the inclination angle is
 found for the models with different temperatures (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=6500$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $8500$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $9500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

As seen in the models of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

, our models also show the blue-shifted peak and the blue-ward asymmetry
 caused by the occultation of the accretion flow by the equatorial disc
 and the stellar disc.
 On the hand, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

 (see their Fig.\SpecialChar ~
9) found a substantial fraction of the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles also shows the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

red-shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 peak, and the P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni profiles which can not be explained by the magnetospherica
l accretion model alone.
 In addition, a recent study by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

 showed that the equivalent width of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from CTTS increases as the inclination angle increases.
 Our model with the magnetospherical accretion flow clearly disagrees with
 their finding.
\layout Standard


