\layout Subsection

Collimated Wind
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:model-wind}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure*}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/atlas_ha_i55_wind_only_final.eps
	scale 90
	keepAspectRatio
	clip

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{H$
\backslash 
alpha$ model profiles computed with wide ranges of the isothermal wind temperature ($T_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}}$) and the wind accerelation rate ($
\backslash 
beta$). The profiles are computed with only wind (no magnetospherical accretion flow or accretion disc). The 'standard' model (Table~
\backslash 
ref{tab:std_parameters}) are applied here. The wind mass-loss rate ($
\backslash 
dot{M}_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}}$), the inclination ($i$) and the degree of collimination ($b$) are fixed at $10^{-8}~{
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}~yr^{-1}}}$,  $55^{
\backslash 
circ}$ and $4.0$
\backslash 
, respectively. The temperature (indicated along the vertical axis) of the model increase from top to bottom, and the wind accerelation rate increases from left to right. The P~Cygni profile are seen for lower $T_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}}$ and lower $
\backslash 
beta$ (slow accerelation) models.  The postion of the absorption the component moves toward the line centre as $
\backslash 
beta$ increases. The effect of line broadening becomes more prominant for higher $T_
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}$ and higher $
\backslash 
beta$ models.}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig:atlas_wind_model}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{figure*}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

As mentioned in earlier, the magnetospherical accretion flow model alone
 cannot explain some of the features seen in observations.
 As an alternative model, we now examine formation of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 in a simple collimated wind as described in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 

.
 The basic wind model parameters introduced earlier are 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

.
 To minimise the number of parameters to be explored, we initially adopt
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.05$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\infty}=200\,\kmps$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}=10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

.
 Further, the angular extent of the wind (the opening angle of the wind)
 is assumed to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{wind}}=80^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 The degree of collimation is initially chosen to be 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 the ratio of the density in polar direction to the density at the edge
 of the wind closest to the accretion disc is about 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cos0^{\circ}/\cos80^{\circ}\right)^{4}\approx10^{3}$
\end_inset 

, for given radii.
 For simplicity, the wind temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 is assumed to be isothermal\SpecialChar \@@.
 Although the line is potentially sensitive
 to the temperature structure of the wind, determination of a self-consistent
 wind temperature is beyond the scope of this paper.
 Readers are refereed to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1982}
\end_inset 

 in which the wind temperature structure is determined by balancing the
 radiative cooling rate (assuming optically thin) with the MHD wave heating
 rate.
 With these parameters kept constant, we examine the characteristics of
 H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles, as a function of the wind acceleration parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and the isothermal wind temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

.
 Dependency on the other parameters will be discussed later in this section.
\layout Standard

Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_wind_disc_model}

\end_inset 

 shows the profile computed at a middle inclination angle 
\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

 for the range of the wind temperature between 
\begin_inset Formula $7000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $9000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, and for the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.0$
\end_inset 

.
 The P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni profile are prominent in the models with lower values of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 (colder and faster acceleration wind).
 As the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases, the position of the blue-shifted absorption component moves
 toward the line centre.
 which can be seen clearly in the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}=7000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 models.
 While the velocity position of absorption component for the fastest acceleratio
n (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.2$
\end_inset 

) is almost at the terminal velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\infty}\sim200\,\kmps$
\end_inset 

), that for the slowest wind acceleration model (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=4.0$
\end_inset 

) is located close the line centre (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim50\,\kmps$
\end_inset 

).
 As one can see in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

, the column density of the gas moving at 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 increases as the wind acceleration faster since the gas moving at 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\infty}$
\end_inset 

 becomes closer to the photosphere.
 At the location where the absorption occurs, the gas is moving faster for
 the models with the faster wind acceleration models; hence, the location
 of the absorption component is bluer as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 becomes smaller (as the wind acceleration faster).
 The figure also shows that the intensity of the emission component increases
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

.
 This is mainly because the density near the photosphere increases (more
 material near the photosphere) as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

); hence, the emissivity of increases.
 Unlike the magnetospherical accretion only models (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_acc_models}

\end_inset 

), the inverse P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni profiles are not seen here, nor the blue-ward asymmetry.
 Because of the absorption component in P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni profile, most of the profiles
 show red-ward asymmetry except for the low temperature wind models with
 high inclinations (not shown here).
\layout Standard

The dependency of the profile on the wind anisotropy parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 is demonstrated in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_wind_b_param}

\end_inset 

.
 Three models presented in the figure have the same mass-loss (
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

), and are computer at inclination angle 
\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 The P\SpecialChar ~
Cygni profile feature becomes more prominent, and the line flux becomes
 smaller as the wind becomes more isotropic (smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 value).
 For a fixed mass-loss rate, the column density of along the line of a sight
 to the observer at a medium inclination angle (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

) increases as 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 decreases (c.f.\SpecialChar ~
equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_final}

\end_inset 

); hence, causing more absorption.
 Further more, the value of the highest density the wind has becomes smaller
 for the.
 As the wind becomes more isotropic, the high gas concentrated more in the
 polar direction has to be spread in the wider angular angles.
 This results in a smaller highest density region in the wind; hence the
 smaller line emissivity.
 For the same reason, the emission in the wings is weaker for the model
 smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 value.
 We also note that the asymmetry around the line centre decreases as the
 wind becomes more isotropic.
 
\layout Standard

The effect of varying the wind mass-loss rate is shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_wind_mdot}

\end_inset 

.
 The line is very sensitive to the mass-loss rate.
 With all other parameters fixed constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 acts as an scaling factor of the wind density (equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_final}

\end_inset 

).
 For the formation of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

, the recombination process and the subsequent downward transition to 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset 

 level.
 Assuming the ionisation fraction remains constant, the recombination rate
 is proportional to the square of wind density.
 We have found the line flux of the models in the figure is approximately
 proportional to the square of the mass-loss rate.
 This very sensitive nature of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 would make the line a good candidate for a mass-loss rate indicator; however,
 without solving the ambiguity of the emission component from the magnetospheric
al accretion flow and the wind, and without knowing the detailed temperature
 structure of the wind, it could provide us a misleading a mass-loss rate
 estimate of a T Tauri star.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/windonly_B_effect2.eps
	scale 45
	clip

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{The effect of wind collimation. The line profiles computed with with $
\backslash 
left(T_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}},~
\backslash 
beta 
\backslash 
right) = 
\backslash 
left( 9000
\backslash 
Kelvin, 0.5
\backslash 
right)$ for  the wind anisotropy parameter $b=0, 2, 4$ are shown in dashed, dotted, and solid respectively.  All the other parameters are same as in Figure~
\backslash 
ref{fig:atlas_wind_model}.  The P~Cygni profile feature become prominant for the spherical wind models (especially in $
\backslash 
beta=0.5$ model) since the collumn density of along the line of a sight of the observer at a medium inclination angle ($i=55^{
\backslash 
circ}$) increases for lower $b$ values for a fixed mass-loss rate of the wind. The blue-ward asymmetry is still present even in the isotropic wind case ($b=0$).}
\end_inset 


