begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/windonly_mdot_effect.eps
	scale 45
	clip

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{The effect of the wind mass-loss rate.  The profiles computed with $
\backslash 
left(T_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}},~
\backslash 
beta 
\backslash 
right) = 
\backslash 
left( 9000
\backslash 
Kelvin, 0.5
\backslash 
right)$, and  $
\backslash 
dot{M}_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}} = 1.0 
\backslash 
times 10^{-8}~
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}
\backslash 
,yr^{-1}}$
\backslash 
, (solid),  $0.5 
\backslash 
times 10^{-8}~
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}
\backslash 
,yr^{-1}}$
\backslash 
, (dotted), and $0.25 
\backslash 
times 10^{-8}~
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}
\backslash 
,yr^{-1}}$
\backslash 
, (dashed) are shown above. The models are computed with only the wind component (no magnetospherical accretion flow or  accretion disc). With all other parameter fixed constant, the mass-loss rate behaves as a scaling factor for the wind density (equation~
\backslash 
ref{eq:wind_density_final}.)}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig:effect_wind_mdot}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Disc 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

collimated wind
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Next, we examine the effect of the size of the inner radius of the disc
 and the distribution of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission region.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_alpha_disc}

\end_inset 

 shows the wind emission profiles computed with and without the accretion
 disc at 
\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 The H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 images (projected on to the plane perpendicular to the observer at the
 location of the star) are also shown in the same figure.
 Both models use the same parameters as in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_wind_model}

\end_inset 

, but with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.5$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}=9000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

).
 The model without the disc can be also considered as a model with a large
 inner radius of the accretion disc, in which none of the wind emission
 region is blocked by the disc --- provided the inclination angle is not
 so high and the disc is not or slightly flared.
\layout Standard

The bipolar nature of the wind is clearly seen in the images.
 The most of the wind emission occurs within a few to a several (depending
 mainly on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

) stellar radii from the star.
 The figure also shows that the accretion disc blocks the wind emission
 the bottom half of the wind which is moving away from the observer.
 This results in the reduction of the wind emission in the red wing.
 The image (mid panel) also shows that the accretion disc is not occulting
 the stellar disc at this inclination; therefore, the ratio of the wind
 emission flux to the photospherical continuum flux becomes slightly smaller
 for the model with the disc.
 This results in the reduction in the peak flux and the flux in the wings
 in the normalised profile shape.
 If the disc becomes more flared (if the opening angle exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

at the outer edge of the accretion disc), the occultation of the stellar
 disc by the accretion could be seen at this inclination angle.
 Although it is not shown here, the continuum level of the two models are
 identical.
 The extent of the line emission is smaller (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.2\,\mathrm{AU}$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim20\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

) compared to the spectro-astrometric observations of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{takami:2003}
\end_inset 

 for RU\SpecialChar ~
Lup and CS Cha which have 1--5 AU scale outflows
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{takami:2003}
\end_inset 

 also showed that some objects (e.g\SpecialChar ~
Z CMa and AS\SpecialChar ~
353A) show the outflows of
 larger scale (
\begin_inset Formula $>50\,\mathrm{AU}$
\end_inset 

) which could be formed by shocks rather than MHD-wave heating (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartmann:1982}
\end_inset 

) or X-ray heating (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{shang:2002}
\end_inset 

).
 
\end_inset 

; however, if a slower wind acceleration rate ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=4$
\end_inset 

) is the emission region become slightly larger (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.4$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU).
 
\layout Standard

Although not shown here, we have computed the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles with the collimated wind and the accretion disc for the same range
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

values as in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_wind_model}

\end_inset 

.
 The inner and the outer radii of the accretion disc are 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{di}}=R_{\mathrm{mi}}=2.2R_{*}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $100\,\mathrm{AU}$
\end_inset 

 respectively, and the disc is slightly flared (see section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Accretion-disc}

\end_inset 

).
 Similar to the case in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_alpha_disc}

\end_inset 

, the line flux of the models with accretion disc decreases to less than
 the half of that without the accretion disc similar to the models shown
 in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_alpha_disc}

\end_inset 

.
 The overall behaviour of the line profile shapes as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 are very similar to that for the models without the accretion disc.
 A significant reduction of the flux in the red wing is seen in the wind
 model with the accretion disc when compared with the wind only model.
 The wings appear to be weaker in these models compared to the wind only
 models because of the lower wind emission flux to the continuum flux as
 briefly mentioned earlier.
 
\layout Standard


