\layout Subsection

Magnetosphere 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

 disc 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset 

collimated wind
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:model-acc-disc-wind}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We examine the characteristics of the line profiles arising from the combination
 of the magnetospherical accretion flow, the wind, and the accretion disc.
 For simplicity, the parameters for the magnetosphere (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 are fixed as in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_acc_models}

\end_inset 

), and the wind mass-loss rate, the isothermal wind temperature and the
 wind anisotropy parameter to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}=10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}=0.1\,\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

), 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The profile computed for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

 is given in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:summary_beta05_t8000}

\end_inset 

, along with the profile computed with the magnetosphere only and that with
 the wind plus accretion disc configurations for a comparison.
 As one can see from the figure, the profile computed for the magnetosphere-wind
-disc hybrid model can be understood as a simple flux sum of the magnetospherica
l component and the wind component.
 
\layout Standard

The effect of changing the ratio of the wind mass-loss rate to mass-accretion
 rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}/\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

) is demonstrated in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_mdot_disc_wind_acc}

\end_inset 

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

 increases the P-Cygni absorption deepens, and the position of minimum flux
 in the absorption trough appears to move blue-ward.
 On the other hand, the emission component becomes stronger as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

 increases.
 At all inclinations (not shown here), the absorption component seems to
 be too strong for the models 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu>0.025$
\end_inset 

 (with this model configuration) compared with the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles (e.g.
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

Again, the profiles with the same ranges of the wind temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

) and the wind acceleration parameter (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

) are computed with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.01$
\end_inset 

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

 times smaller than the value suggested by MHD simulations (e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{konigl:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 The small value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

 is chosen to avoid unrealistically strong absorption component of the P-Cyg
 profile as seen in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_mdot_disc_wind_acc}

\end_inset 

.
 In general, even with small values of the anisotropy parameter (
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset 

), the absorption component is too strong when compared observations.
 The model H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles computed for the same ranges of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

, with the parameters of the magnetosphere fixed as in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:acc_inclination_effect}

\end_inset 

, are shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 along with the model with only the magnetosphere, for a comparison.
 The figure shows that the position of the wind absorption component moves
 toward the line centre as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 becomes larger.
 Although little wind emission is seen in this temperature range, it becomes
 more important in a model with a higher temperature and a wind mass-loss
 rate.
 The profiles shown in this figure understood as the combination of the
 emission from the magnetosphere and the absorption of the flux by the wind
 component.
 The emission from the accretion disc is negligible, but the absorption
 of the continuum flux from the photosphere by the disc is important for
 predicting the line strength correctly.
 
\layout Standard

Although the profiles shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 are those of a single inclination angle (
\begin_inset Formula $i=55^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

), they are very similar to the Type II-B and III-B of the observed CTTS
 H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

), which are impossible to be explained by the magnetospherical accretion
 flow models (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
