\layout Subsection

Disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:result-discwind-knigge}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

As an alternative model for the bipolar wind models (with the combination
 of the magnetosphere and the accretion disc) shown in Figures\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_wind_model}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

, we have also considered the disc-wind model 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 

 as briefly described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

.
 The former resembles the density structure of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in large scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) which described in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 

, and the latter in small scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) of the same model.
 The main difference between the two models are in their density structure.
 For a given radius, the density increases toward the polar direction in
 the former model, but the density increases toward the equatorial plane
 for the models presented here.
 
\layout Standard

First, the disc wind models without the magnetosphere are considered.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_only}

\end_inset 

 shows the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles computed using only the disc-wind component (c.f.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_discwind}

\end_inset 

) for the same isothermal disc-wind temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

) and the wind acceleration parameter (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

) ranges used for the bipolar wind models.
 The parameters used for the central star are as in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Continuum-Source}

\end_inset 

, and the other disc-wind parameters are summarised in Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_discwind_parameters}

\end_inset 

.
 The figure shows that the wind emission increases 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

 increase.
 Similar to the bipolar wind models, the location of the P-Cyg absorption
 component moves toward the line centre as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases.
 The morphology of the profile exhibited by the model changes from FU-Ori
 type (IV-B) for the models with small 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 to III-B and II-B types (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

) as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases.
 Although not shown here, we find that the profile shapes are relatively
 insensitive to the value of the wind collimation parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

.
 The dependency on the disc wind mass-loss rate of the profile shape is
 similar to that of the collimated wind models (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_mdot_disc_wind_acc}

\end_inset 

) .
\layout Standard

We now consider the models computed with the combination of the disc-wind
 and the magnetospherical accretion components.
 The parameters used for the magnetosphere are set to be same as in the
 case for Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:acc_inclination_effect}

\end_inset 

, and are kept constant for simplicity.
 The mass-loss rate of the disc wind is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{dw}}=10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 (i.e.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\dot{M}_{\mathrm{dw}}/\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset 

) Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 shows the models profiles computed using the same ranges of the disc-wind
 temperature and the wind acceleration parameter as in the previous cases.
 
\layout Standard

As in the disc wind only models (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_only}

\end_inset 

), the location of the absorption component moves toward the line centre
 as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 increases (as the wind acceleration slower).
 The figure shows that in the models with smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

, the line emission from the magnetosphere dominates.
 On the other hand, in the models with larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

, the emission from the disc wind dominates.
 Compared to the observation of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{alencar:2000}
\end_inset 

, the lines are too strong for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T_{\mathrm{dw}},\,\beta\right)=\left(9000\,\mathrm{K},\,2.0\right)$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(9000\,\mathrm{K},\,1.0\right)$
\end_inset 

 models.
 The wide varieties of profile shapes are see in this set of models which
 resembles II-B, III-B, IV-B, II-R and III-R
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed false

\layout Standard

Not shown here, but seen in the models with higher inclinations.
\end_inset 

 types of the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

).
 The shaper of the primary and secondary peaks in the profiles are slightly
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

rounder
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 compared to those of the accretion, collimated wind, disc hybrid model
 shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

.
 The rounder peaks are caused by the rotation of the wind.
 The profiles from the disc wind models are affected more by the rotational
 motion of the wind since the gas is more concentrated toward the equator,
 but in the models with the collimated wind the gas is concentrated more
 in the polar directions.
\layout Standard

We note the ambiguity seen between some of the disc-wind only models and
 the disc-wind, magnetosphere hybrid models.
 For example, the disc-wind only model with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T_{\mathrm{wind}},\,\beta\right)=\left(8000\,\mathrm{K},\,1.0\right)$
\end_inset 

 in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_only}

\end_inset 

 and the disc-wind model with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T_{\mathrm{wind}},\,\beta\right)=\left(9000\,\mathrm{K},\,0.5\right)$
\end_inset 

 in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 give very similar profiles.
 Given such an observed profile, it is difficult to distinguish if the emission
 is dominated by the accretion or the wind unless some other lines, not
 affected associated with wind or magnetosphere, are used simultaneously.
 
\layout Standard

The general characteristics of the profiles from the disc-wind, magnetosphere
 hybrid model (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

) are very similar to those of the disc, collimated wind, magnetosphere
 hybrid model (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

).
 The main difference between these two sets of models is the mass-loss rate
 to the mass accretion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

.
 While the models presented in this section use 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.1$
\end_inset 

 which is consistent wite the MHD jet models (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

), the models in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 use much smaller value (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.01$
\end_inset 

).
 
