\layout Subsection

An example model fit of T\SpecialChar ~
Tau
\layout Standard

As a demonstrative purpose, we present a model fit of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 observation of a classical T Tauri star (T\SpecialChar ~
Tau) obtained by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{vink:2005}
\end_inset 

.
 T\SpecialChar ~
Tau is known to be a triple system (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koresko:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 One of the star in the system T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N (a prototype for T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars) is dominatin
g in optical (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{calvet:1994}
\end_inset 

).
 The rotational velocity and the rotational period of the star found by
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{herbst:1987}
\end_inset 

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i=19.5\pm2.5\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.80\,\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The inclination of the disc is known to be relatively small (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $i=29^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{akeson:2002}
\end_inset 

).
 There is a rather large scatter in the previously estimated the accretion
 rates e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $3\times10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{johns-krull:2000}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3.1-5.7\right)\times10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{calvet:2004}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

For the photospheric model, the following parameters from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{calvet:2004}
\end_inset 

 are adopted: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{eff}}=5500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{*}=1.9\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{*}=2.9\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

.
 The standard geometry for the magnetosphere (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}=2.2\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}=3.0\, R_{*}$
\end_inset 

) and the bipolar wind configuration (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

) are used for simplicity.
 Again, our purpose here is not to obtain the best fit parameters, but rather
 it is to examine if the model is capable of reasonably reproducing the
 data from a real object, in this case, T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N.
 The main parameters here 1.\SpecialChar ~
the temperature of the magnetospherical accretion
 flow (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset 

), 2.\SpecialChar ~
the mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}$
\end_inset 

), 3.\SpecialChar ~
the temperature of the wind (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

), and 4.\SpecialChar ~
the wind mass-loss rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M_{\mathrm{wind}}}$
\end_inset 

).
 The inclination angle was simplify adopted from 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{akeson:2002}
\end_inset 

 and set to 
\begin_inset Formula $i=29^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:ttau_model}

\end_inset 

 shows the result of a model fit.
 The amount of veiling near H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is very small (
\begin_inset Formula $<0.01$
\end_inset 

) for T\SpecialChar ~
Tau, according to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{basri:1990}
\end_inset 

; hence, the observation is not corrected for veiling.
 The model consists of the magnetosphere, the bipolar wind, and the accretion
 disc (with a large hole i.e.
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5$\, AU

\end_inset 

.
 The parameters used for the model fit are: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=9600\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}=8000\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=1.0\times10^{-8}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}=2.5\times10^{-9}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

.
 The figures shows that the agreement between the model and the observation
 is quite reasonable although the line wings are slightly stronger in the
 models.
 In this example, the main profile feature is defined by the emission from
 the magnetosphere, but the blue side of the profile is affected by the
 absorption by the wind.
 Although not shown here for clarity, the peak flux near the line centre
 is also affected by the wind absorption (causing about 10 per cent reduction)
 compared to the profile computer with magnetosphere only model (similar
 effect also seen in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

).
 If the fit was performed by ignoring the wind, the temperature and the
 mass-accretion rate of the magnetospherical accretion flow will be underestimat
ed.
 A better approach to a model fit is a simultaneous fitting of multiple
 lines.
 For example, the near-infrared lines such as Pa
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and Br
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 should be used to determined the mass-loss rate since these lines are much
 less affected by the wind.
 Using the mass-loss rate from these lines, H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 can be used to determine the wind mass-loss rate.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ttau_compare.eps
	scale 45
	clip

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{center}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
caption{Comparison of the observed H$
\backslash 
alpha$ profile of T~Tau and the profile computed with the hybrid model, which consist of the magnetosphere, the colliminated wind, and the accretion disc (with a large hole i.e. $
\backslash 
sim 5$~AU). The inclination angle $30^
\backslash 
circ$ is used.  The maximum temperature of the magnetosphere ($T_{
\backslash 
mathrm{max}}$) and the isothermal wind temperature used here are 9600~K and 8000~K respetively. The mass-accretion rate ($
\backslash 
dot{M}_{
\backslash 
mathrm{acc}}$) and the mass-loss rate ($
\backslash 
dot{M}_{
\backslash 
mathrm{wind}}$) are $1.0 
\backslash 
times 10^{-8}
\backslash 
,
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}
\backslash 
,yr^{-1}}$ and $2.5 
\backslash 
times 10^{-9}
\backslash 
,
\backslash 
mathrm{M_{
\backslash 
sun}
\backslash 
,yr^{-1}}$ resplectively. } 
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig:ttau_model}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
end{figure}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
