\end_inset 


\layout Subsection

Which wind model?
\layout Standard

In the previous sections, two possible geometrical configurations for the
 wind from CTTS were considered: 1.
 the bipolar wind, and 2.\SpecialChar ~
the disc wind.
 While the material more concentrated toward the polar regions for a given
 radius in the first case, the material is more concentrated toward the
 equatorial plane in the second case.
 As mentioned earlier, the bipolar wind morel resembles the density distribution
 of the jet MHD simulation of e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in large scale (
\begin_inset Formula $>10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU), and the disc wind model resembles that in smaller scale (
\begin_inset Formula $<10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU).
 
\layout Standard

The distinct difference in the density dependency on the polar angles in
 two models should be apparent in the inclination angle dependency on the
 shapes of the line profiles.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_inclination_compare}

\end_inset 

 shows the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles computed for 1.\SpecialChar ~
the disc, bipolar-wind, accretion hybrid model (section
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-acc-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

) and 2.\SpecialChar ~
the disc-wind, magnetosphere hybrid model (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:result-discwind-knigge}

\end_inset 

) at inclination angles 
\begin_inset Formula $i=10^{\circ},\,55^{\circ},\,80^{\circ}$
\end_inset 

.
 Both models include the magnetospherical accretion component with the same
 parameters used as in sections\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-acc-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:result-discwind-knigge}

\end_inset 

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{max}}=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}=1\times10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Mainly because of the geometrical configuration, the P-Cyg absorption feature
 weakens as the inclination increases for the model with the bipolar wind.
 The optical depth to an observer is higher (from the wind emission region)
 for with a lower inclination angle with this geometry.
 Although not shown here, this tendency of the inclination dependency holds
 for the models with bipolar wind models for wide ranges of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

.
 For the model with the disc wind, the absorption becomes stronger as the
 inclination becomes larger .
 The optical depth to an observer becomes larger as the inclination increases
 in this geometry.
 
\layout Standard

Similarly, the line equivalent width increases as the inclination angle
 increases for the model with the bipolar wind, it decreases as the inclination
 angle increases for the model with the disc wind.
 With the models with only magnetosphere (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-acc}

\end_inset 

), we have also found that the line equivalent width decreases as the inclinatio
n increases in those models (see Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:acc_inclination_effect}

\end_inset 

).
 Interestingly, the observational study of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

 showed that the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 line equivalent width of CTTS increases as the inclination angle increases.
 Only the models with the bipolar wind agree with the trend seen in their
 observation.
 Although the uncertainty in the inclination angles of the observed object
 might be large, a larger sample in addition to that of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

 for further investigation of the inclination dependency on the line profile
 will be extremely useful for finding a possible wind configuration of CTTS.
\layout Standard

Despite the inclination angle dependency of the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 favouring the models with bipolar wind, there are some aspects of this
 model are not quite consistent with the magneto-centrifugal launched jet
 numerical models (e.g 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

).
 First, in section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:model-acc-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

, we found that the ratio of the mass-loss to mass-accretion rates had to
 be rather small (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu<\sim0.025$
\end_inset 

), in order not to have an unrealistically strong P-Cyg absorption component,
 compared to the MHD simulations suggested 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{koenigl:200}
\end_inset 

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\approx0.1$
\end_inset 

.
 On contrary, the models with the disc wind (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:result-discwind-knigge}

\end_inset 

) using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0.1$
\end_inset 

 reproduces the profiles (Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

) similar to that seen in observations.
 Further, the MHD models predict that the wind/jet becomes collimated well
 above the disc plane (
\begin_inset Formula $>10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU), but our bipolar wind model are collimated (density enhanced toward
 in the polar direction) from right outside of the magnetosphere.
 Unless the origin of the wind is from the central star itself, the density
 distribution used for the bipolar wind is not quite consistent with the
 near field of the MHD jet models, considering that the most of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 emission occurs within a few to a several radii of the magnetosphere (Figure.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:effect_alpha_disc}

\end_inset 

).
 The density structure used for the disc wind model, however, is very similar
 to that of MHD simulations in the near field where the most of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 wind emission occurs.
 Considering the issues mentioned above, it is not possible to favour the
 bipolar wind model to the disc wind model without further observational
 constraints.
 Perhaps, the line variability studies in an eclipsing binary system would
 help.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{figure*}
\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
begin{center}
\end_inset 


