\end_inset 


\layout Section

Conclusions
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Conclusions}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We have presented the disc--wind--magnetosphere hybrid radiative transfer
 models for classical T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars, and detailed studies of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 formation from their complex to circumstellar environment and to understand
 the wide variety emission line profiles seen in observations.
 The two types of wind models considered are 1.\SpecialChar ~
the bipolar wind model in
 the wind is originated from the star itself (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 

; Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

), and 2.\SpecialChar ~
the disc-wind model in which the wind originates from the inner
 part of the accretion disc (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Alternative-model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

; Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_discwind}

\end_inset 

).
 We found that both wind models combined with the magnetospherical accretion
 flow reproduces the wide variety of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 profiles (Figures\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_disc_wind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_discwind_acc_model}

\end_inset 

) seen in the observations.
 
\layout Standard

The inclination dependency of the line equivalent width predicted by the
 bipolar wind model agree with trends seen in the observation, but the disc-wind
 model does not.
 With the standard magnetospherical configuration (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

), the ratio of the mass-loss to mass-accretion rates (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

) used in the bipolar wind was set to be 4--10 times smaller than that predicate
d by magneto-hydrodynamical (MHD) calculations (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\mu\sim1.0;$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

) to avoid the blue-shifted absorption component becoming unrealistically
 too strong; however 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset 

 used in the disc-wind models are consistent with MHD calculations.
 
\layout Standard

Using the model results, we examined the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 spectroscopic classification proposed by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
\end_inset 

, and discuss the basic physical conditions that reproduce the profiles
 in each classified type.
 Using the hybrid model, we also fit the observed H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 from the optical component of T\SpecialChar ~
Tau triple system (T\SpecialChar ~
Tau\SpecialChar ~
N).
 The agreement between the model and the observation is excellent; however,
 we could not confirm the uniqueness of the fit.
 The ratio of the mass-loss to mass-accretion rate was found to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.2$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Although not attempted in this paper, a better approach for determining
 the mass-loss and mass-accretion rate consistently is to model multiples
 lines simultaneously.
 For example, the mass-accretion rate of an object can be determined more
 easily by modelling Pa
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 and Br
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 since there is no/little wind effect seen in these lines.
 The mass-accretion rate then can be used to model H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 to find the wind mass-loss rate.
 
\layout Standard

Similar model configurations used here may be also applicable to Herbig
 Ae/Be and brown dwarfs since their H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 observations also exhibit evidences of the outflow and inflow (REFS), but
 no model has been developed to explain the phenomenon.
 Further investigation on the possibility of applying our model to these
 objects are needed.
 
\layout Standard

Future works should include the followings: (1)\SpecialChar ~
Improving the wind models.
 The parametrisation of the wind density structure should be changed to
 follow more closely that of MHD simulations.
 The wind temperature structure should be calculated self-consistently (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{martin:1996}
\end_inset 

).
 (2)\SpecialChar ~
Computing the line profiles using the density structure from MHDs directly.
 Check the consistency, and give feedback to the MHD models which are needed
 to be tested against observational data.
 (3)\SpecialChar ~
Spectropolarimetric study to explore the geometry and the rotation of
 the disc (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{vink:2005}
\end_inset 

).
 (4)\SpecialChar ~
Modelling of the extended H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 and spectro-astrometric observations (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{takami:2003}
\end_inset 

;
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

).
 (5)\SpecialChar ~
Line variability study using a 3D radiative transfer model (e.g.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{kurosawa:2005a}
\end_inset 

) to probe the geometrical structure.
\layout Standard


