\layout Subsection
a8175 2
Classification scheme proposed by Reipurth et.
 al (1996)
d8179 8
a8186 2
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed
d8190 2
a8191 2
\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
d8194 1
a8194 2
proposed the two-dimentional classification of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
d8196 3
d8200 1
a8200 10
 emission profiles of T\SpecialChar ~
Tauri stars and Herbig Ae/Be stars.
 Their classification scheme contains four classes (I, II, III and IV) differenc
iated by the ratio of the secondary-to-primary emission components in the
 profiles.
 Each classes are devided into two sub-classes (B and R) which depends whether
 the absorption componet is on the blue or red side.
 Readers are refered to Fig.\SpecialChar ~
4 of their paper.
 Figure\SpecialChar ~
a8201 1
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:atlas_reipurth}
d8203 1
d8206 7
a8212 4
 shows the sample model profiles which are classified according to the definitio
n of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed
d8216 5
a8220 2
\backslash 
citet{reipurth:1996}
d8222 6
d8229 2
a8230 6
.
 The combinatioin of the wind, magnetospherical accretion, and accretion
 disc can reasonably reproduce all the classes of the profiles seen in observati
ons.
 The model parameters used to reproduce the profiles in the figure are given
 in Table\SpecialChar ~
a8231 1
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:classification}
d8234 3
a8237 3
 along with the comments on possible physical conditions which leads to
 the profiles in each class.
 
d8240 10
a8249 4
Within the parameter space covered, we find it is difficult to produce Type
 I type profile, which is very symmetric around the line centre and without
 any absorption feature, if the wind component is added in the model.
